<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1744,2011]" pageId="0" pageNumber="596">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1953,1976]" pageId="0" pageNumber="596">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Truuverk &amp; Vaitonis" authorityYear="2019" box="[324,532,1952,1976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" species="sirotka">
<emphasis box="[324,532,1952,1976]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="596">Blepharosis sirotka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[549,646,1953,1976]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1897,1919]" captionTargetBox="[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Blepharosis spp. male adults. 1. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 2. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (ASV); 3. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 4. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 5. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai (PGM); 6. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai PGY4911m (PGM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715700/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="596">Figs 1–4</figureCitation>
) is an unmistakable species among the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boursin" authorityYear="1964" box="[1086,1212,1952,1976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1086,1212,1952,1976]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="596">Blepharosis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The new species is best distinguished by the unicolorous brown body and forewing in which only the ochre or pale brown orbicular and
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
reniform stigmata are conspicuous, while the rest of the wing pattern remains conjectural. It is very different externally from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[210,402,185,209]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis box="[210,402,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[417,512,186,209]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1897,1919]" captionTargetBox="[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Blepharosis spp. male adults. 1. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 2. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (ASV); 3. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 4. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 5. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai (PGM); 6. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai PGY4911m (PGM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715700/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
) (the only close congener regarding their male genital structures) which has narrower, more variegated forewing; whitish to pale yellow reniform stigma, of which the continuation along the lower cellvein reaches the base of wing; brown coloration restricted to the middle, while the outer part of the basal and the inner half of the marginal areas are suffused with whitish-grey well-defined antemedial, postmedial and subterminal crosslines and whitish-grey covered veins; and much lighter hindwing inner area.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
In the male genitalia features, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Truuverk &amp; Vaitonis" authorityYear="2019" box="[528,632,359,383]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sirotka">
<emphasis box="[528,632,359,383]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">B. sirotka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[648,744,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1764,1786]" captionTargetBox="[162,1436,195,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,191,1743]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Blepharosis spp. male genitalia. 7. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 8. B. sirotka sp. n., paratype, China, Sichuan, PGY4924m (ASV); 9. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai, PGY4911m (PGM);" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715702/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Figs 7, 8</figureCitation>
) differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[898,1092,359,383]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis box="[898,1092,359,383]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1108,1174,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1764,1786]" captionTargetBox="[162,1436,195,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,191,1743]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Blepharosis spp. male genitalia. 7. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 8. B. sirotka sp. n., paratype, China, Sichuan, PGY4924m (ASV); 9. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai, PGY4911m (PGM);" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715702/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) by the apically smaller horned uncus; terminally prominent cucullus, stronger, in the basal section much broader, slightly longer digitus which is partly fused with the continuation of the ampullar plate and the somewhat shorter aedeagus with smooth ventral carinal plate and with slightly more ample vesica armed with basally thicker distal cornuti.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715700" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3715700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715700/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" startId="1.[151,258,1897,1919]" targetBox="[165,1430,541,1866]" targetPageId="1">
