<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1858,2020]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">
The entire structure of the male genitalia (shape of uncus, valvae, juxta, the lack of the clasper and ampulla and the vesica configuration) of the new species is, however, so strongly similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[1074,1270,1892,1916]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis box="[1074,1270,1892,1916]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that it became necessary to compare their DNA to decide their taxonomic relationship. The separation of the two taxa as two distinct species is further supported by their different habitats and the unusually late flight period of the new species compared to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[151,343,1996,2020]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis box="[151,343,1996,2020]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is a typically summer species.
</paragraph>
